<br>
I've found exp areas that are virutually empty, often just up a hill from a siabra camp that's shared by 3 groups. There's a nice camp of anger sprites, many of them grouped into pairs, following the river north, past Druim Ligen, almost to where the river turns up into the zone wall. <br>
<br>
East of East Lough Derg, you can move in a long way from the water. If you hug the water, I wouldn't be surprised to find most places camped. But if you strike out east, you may find fertile hunting grounds. I haven't heard anyone mention veil wisps as a great place to hunt, especially for a group like you're mentioning. <br>
<br>
Take advantage of the size of your group and explore! Move east of Lough Derg or north/northwest of TNN, see what you can find!<br>
<br>
I've also found many of my future hunting areas while doing quests. Veil wisps are a perfect example of that. <br>
<br>
So far, I've always been rewarded by exploring.<br>
<br>
In fact, it reminds me very much of my time living right outside Yellowstone National Park. It's packed in the summertime, crazy crowds. Lots of people would come into the bar I worked at and complained about it. <br>
<br>
I'd tell them what a park ranger friend told me. 95% of the people who visit Yellowstone only go 100 feet off the road in any direction. Then they get back in their cars and zoom off to the next animal jam.<br>
<br>
Obviously, exploring Yellowstone is a bit riskier than DAoC, but the model is true. Get off the roads, cut through the forests, take your deaths as a trade off for what you're learning...have a rez capable partner stay behind you while exploring, so they can rez you right back in if you have an accident. <br>
<br>
Also, my favorite time to explore is right after I level. Since you can't delevel, I'll risk exploring in unknown areas when I don't have any exp to lose :-) <p><b>Gallatin</b><p>
